article.description: Cuttino Mobley scored 38 points and nailed the go-ahead 3-pointer as the Rockets dominated the final five minutes of a 101-98 victory over the the Seattle SuperSonics.
article.headline: Rockets' 13-0 run buries Sonics in fourth
article.linkText: Mobley, 'Raging' Thomas propels Rockets past Sonics
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Kenny Thomas isn't sure about his new nickname, but he's glad to get the attention.
Thomas

Thomas scored 16 points, including six in the final 3:42 of the game, helping the Houston Rockets to a 101-98 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics on Tuesday. Two of Thomas' final three baskets came by driving the lane, a muscle play for which he is starting to become known. Coach Rudy Tomjanovich calls Thomas his "Raging Bull." "It's always something," Thomas said with a smile when asked about the nickname. "I'll take it, I guess, if he's going to give me more time late in the game. "It feels good that they're going to me late in games now. They didn't do that my first couple of years." Tomjanovich believes Thomas deserves the important role. "He's just a raging bull," Tomjanovich said. "He's one of the hardest to guard in the league at the 'four' spot. He had a tremendous game." His teammates agree. "Kenny's a clutch player," said Cuttino Mobley, who had 38 points. "He doesn't get recognized a lot, but we love and respect him. He does everything for us." The SuperSonics certainly recognized him when Thomas scored four points and got two rebounds in a 13-0 run that turned the game around in the fourth quarter. His big plays in the final 3:42 also impressed Seattle. "Kenny Thomas is a super player and he's getting better all the time," said Gary Payton, who had 24 for the SuperSonics. "He made a great play at the end and it really hurt us." Coach Nate McMillan lauded the Rockets' effort in the final minutes. "They kept going to a number of different guys until they found one who was working," McMillan said. "Thomas was the last guy they went to and he created some shots." Steve Francis just missed a triple-double with 16 points, 11 rebounds and eight assists. Brent Barry scored 20 points and Desmond Mason had 18. The SuperSonics still have won eight of their last 11 and 11 of 15. Houston led through most of the first quarter, but could never stretch the margin to more than six points. Mobley had nine points as the Rockets were on top 24-21 after one. Early in the second quarter, Mason scored four points in an 8-0 SuperSonics run to a 31-26 lead with 8:22 to play. Houston regained the lead for much of the quarter as Mobley scored 12 more points. But Barry hit two 3-pointers in the last 2.7 seconds of the second quarter to give Seattle a 54-51 halftime lead. Walt Williams had nine and Mobley seven points in the third quarter as Houston came back to tie it 76-76 at the end of the period. In the fourth quarter, Seattle got four points each from Barry and Predrag Drobnjak in an 8-0 run. That gave the SuperSonics their biggest lead of the night at 88-81 with 7:21 to play. Houston then went on a 13-0 run with the help of consecutive 3-pointers from Francis, Mobley and Eddie Griffin. Game notes
Kevin Willis was placed on the injured list with a left ankle sprain and Oscar Torres was activated from the injured list on Tuesday. ... Houston's Terence Morris missed the game with the flu. ... The Rockets, who play at Minnesota on Wednesday, are 4-10 on the first night of back-to-backs and 3-10 on the second nights. ... Seattle's Vladimir Radmanovic sat out the game with a right big toe sprain. ... Seattle, which lost at Dallas on Monday, is 11-6 in the first games of back-to-backs and 7-10 in second games. ... Payton had no steals and is still nine short of 2,000 for his NBA career.
